<br>
The best thing to do at this level is to learn your spells inside and out and know what they can and can't do.  At level 16 you pretty much have the basic spells, it doesn't get all too much different... just more toys to play with down the road.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Learning them now will make you stand out later.  My suggestion would be to bind yourself on the dock in Freeport, take the boat going toward BB, go past Sister Island and jump off the boat on the right side when you pass through the two rock formations.  Those are the two sirens, they won't aggro until attacked and they don't give faction.  Make a pet and buff up.  This was the all time best way for me to learn about 1) my pet, 2) my spells, and 3) crowd control.  On those rocks there's really only a few options: live, die, gate, or swim for it and die in the water because the sirens WILL chase you.  I leveled 2 enchanters from 12 to 16 here and it was the absolute best practice for keeping myself alive by my own means, a skill that my group sure appreciates at this stage of my game.  Sure I died a lot but once I figured out what I was doing it was like a finely tuned piano.  Those two sirens are *fast* and they hit *hard* against a wimpy enchanter.  And with only your spells, a weapon, and a pet at your disposal you really force yourself to test the limits.  If you finish off those two sirens you can swim to the other side, run around the bottom of the rocks (aqua goblins up top... greenies, but annoying) and there's a single siren that spawns there.<br>
<br>
Concerning religion, this is up to you.  NPC faction is strange... if you don't mind spending time restoring or gaining faction in order to complete a quest then I'd say stick with your current enchanter.  You'll do fine.  Otherwise it's never too late to start over.  My first enchanter was about to turn level 20 and I restarted her as agnostic... best decision I ever made.  That's strictly up to you.<br>
<br>
Concerning the flux spells... if the mob is resisting the spell you need to tashan it quickly and try to stun it.  If it keeps interrupting your flux then you need to work on timing when you start casting vs when the mob is hitting you.  Later on you'll get more color stuns so you can chain stun and each lasts a bit longer.  Very effective for interrupting casting mobs and stunning about 4 or 5 that aggro'd on you so can dash to a safe spot and AE mez the pack. <p>Dellenn<BR>
41st Dark Elf Enchanter<BR>
Circle of Three, Povar<BR>
